The length of the statement " RockMigrationHelper.AddDefinedValueAttributeValue( "0894EDBA-8FC8-4433-877C-53351A06A8B7"' "EADE1EC5-E05B-4956-973E-BBBA2A02F0C0"' @"

<p>The gift is to be used with cheerfulness; that is' joyousness which is ready to do anything: <br />Romans 12:8. We see this gift in Dorcas as well as Helps/Services: Acts 9:36. Mercy will be <br />manifested in good deeds: James 2:15'16. All believers are commanded to have mercy: <br />Matthew 9:13; Luke 10:37.<br />Probable characteristics (often latent):</p>

<ul>

<li>You find it easy to identify with the feelings of someone in pain.</li>

<li>You cry easily or show emotions when you see or hear things that sadden you.</li>

<li>When someone is sharing something deep with you' you find yourself crying when they do.</li>

<li>Your immediate reactions when you see someone in difficulty is to want to reach out and help.</li>

<li>You sometimes become bitter because of the injustices someone else suffers.</li>

<li>Most people would see you as an empathetic person.</li>

<li>People come to you with problems not because of some practical things you do' but because you have the ability to understand what they are going through and can console them.</li>

<li>You have the ability to “cheer up” people who are going through deep personal struggles.</li>

<li>Your prayer life includes the needs of the many personal struggles you know people are experiencing.</li>

<li>When you are finished having someone share with you' many times you find yourself emotionally drained.</li>

<li>You enjoy calling on people in the hospital or who are sick or going through some difficulty.</li>

</ul>

The length of the statement " RockMigrationHelper.AddDefinedValueAttributeValue( "0F8D41AA-7236-40BF-AA37-980BCCF4A881"' "EADE1EC5-E05B-4956-973E-BBBA2A02F0C0"' @"

<p>All Christians are called to evangelize (Matthew 28:19'20; Acts 5:42; 2 Timothy 4:5). It is an <br />office of the New Testament church (Acts 21:8). This gift not only evangelizes but also equips <br />others to do it as well (Ephesians 4:11). There are two aspects of this gift:</p>

<ul>

<li>Public:

<ul>

<li>Philip (Acts 8:5-13)</li>

<li>Paul (Acts 17:19-34)</li>

</ul>

</li>

<li>Private:

<ul>

<li>Philip (Acts 8:26-39)</li>

<li>Paul (Acts 16:25-33)</li>

</ul>

</li>

</ul>

<p>It provides growth for existing churches and helps establish newly-planted churches (2 Timothy <br />4:5; Acts 17:10-15). It normally does not include cross-cultural evangelism. <br />Biblical examples:</p>

<ul>

<li>Philip: Acts 8:5-13; 26-39</li>

<li>Paul: Acts 16: 25-33; 17:19-34</li>

</ul>

<p>Probable characteristics of this gift:</p>

<ul>

<li>Your prayer life reveals a burden for those who do not know Christ.</li>

<li>You enjoy meeting people and make new friends easily.</li>

<li>You feel comfortable with strangers and talk about many different subjects.</li>

<li>You are able to articulate your faith easily and people respond positively.</li>

<li>You enjoy being around people.</li>

<li>You have a burden to share the gospel of Jesus Christ publicly or with individuals.</li>

<li>You are able to persuade or help people reach decisions to commit their lives to Christ.</li>

<li>You are not satisfied with “superficial commitments;” you want people to become full <br />disciples of Christ.</li>

<li>You have an inner unrest at the thought of people dying and going to hell.</li>

<li>You have the ability to move conversations in a direction of the other person’s relationship with Christ.</li>

<li>When with non-Christians' their position with Christ inevitably comes up.</li>

<li>Your prayers contain the names of many people who are not Christians or those you are training to share Christ.</li>

<li>People enjoy being trained by you to share their faith.</li>

<li>You have the ability to motivate and train others to share their faith effectively</li>

</ul>

" ); " is 2869.

The length of the statement " RockMigrationHelper.AddDefinedValueAttributeValue( "13C40209-F41D-4C1D-83D3-2EC530588245"' "EADE1EC5-E05B-4956-973E-BBBA2A02F0C0"' @"

<p>This is the behind the scenes worker. These people enjoy such tasks as:</p>

<ul>

<li>Washing dishes</li>

<li>Cooking meals</li>

<li>Setting up meeting areas</li>

<li>Operating sound equipment</li>

</ul>

<p>This is one of the more important gifts and often the least practiced. Without it' all other gifts <br />must perform functions out of their own gift mix' inhibiting their effectiveness. Therefore' the <br />people with the gift of helps/service free others up to use their own gifts. We all should <br />exemplify this gift as characterized by Christ. But a person who truly has this gift personifies it <br />to the extreme and is recharged by exercising it.<br />Biblical examples:</p>

<ul>

<li>Acts 6: -- Men relieved Apostles of work</li>

<li>Acts 13:5 -- John Mark helped Paul and Barnabas</li>

<li>2 Timothy 4:11</li>

<li>1 Peter 5:13</li>

<li>Acts 19:22 -- Paul had two other helpers</li>

<li>Romans 16:1-4 -- Priscilla and Aquilla</li>

<li>Colossians 4:12' 13 -- Epaphras</li>

</ul>

<p>Probable characteristics of this gift:</p>

<ul>

<li>You have an uncanny ability to see needs.</li>

<li>You work by yourself or in small groups.</li>

<li>You have a desire to help others.</li>

<li>You do not need to receive public recognition for what you do.</li>

<li>You enjoy doing “little things” that can help other people.</li>

<li>You do not enjoy handling major leadership or overseeing responsibilities.</li>

<li>You enjoy doing things for someone else that enables them to use their gifts more fully.</li>

<li>You do not have to ask what needs to be done; you can see needs.</li>

<li>You have the ability to sense the temporal needs of others.</li>

<li>In the church' you have a willingness to do jobs which will allow leadership gifts to be used in a fruitful way.</li>

<li>Sometimes you feel guilty or envious because you do not have one of the more “obvious” gifts that others seem to possess.</li>

</ul>

The length of the statement " RockMigrationHelper.AddDefinedValueAttributeValue( "3EB352F3-F624-4ED6-A9EE-7951B71B1952"' "EADE1EC5-E05B-4956-973E-BBBA2A02F0C0"' @"

<p>All Christians should be able to distinguish between right and wrong (Hebrews 5:14; 1 John 4:1). <br />This gift involves insight into circumstances which ordinarily could not be known' so that <br />motives may be ascertained (Acts 5:1-10). At times' this gift will reveal a person’s sincerity in <br />the course of a conversation (Acts 8:23). This gift is easily counterfeited by Satan (Luke 4:33' 34; <br />Acts 16:17). Biblical examples include Matthew 9:4.<br />Probable characteristics of this gift:</p>

<ul>

<li>You are very observant to what people say.</li>

<li>You tend to notice “body language” that is not consistent with what the person is <br />saying.</li>

<li>You almost have a sixth sense about what is being said or is happening which cannot <br />always be explained.</li>

<li>Your intuitions are often correct.</li>

<li>You hesitate to speak to others of their motives because they may not be receptive.</li>

<li>You sometimes gossip about a “feeling” you have with regard to a person rather than <br />confront the person involved.</li>

<li>You do not view yourself as a “witch hunter”.</li>

<li>Certain events often confirm a premonition you have had.</li>

<li>You have an analytical mind.</li>

<li>People see you as a very perceptive person.</li>

<li>Your prayers often consist of asking God what you should do with your intuitions.</li>

</ul>

The length of the statement " RockMigrationHelper.AddDefinedValueAttributeValue( "462A5D10-6DEA-43D7-96EF-8F82FF1E2E14"' "EADE1EC5-E05B-4956-973E-BBBA2A02F0C0"' @"

<p>This gift is intended to be communicated. This is why it is called the “message of knowledge” <br />(1 Corinthians 12:8). This gift sometimes “puffs up” if kept to yourself (1 Corinthians 8:1). <p>There were positions in the New Testament church for some who had this gift (Acts 13:1). <br />As a result of the use of this gift' people will not just know more' but their behavior will actually <br />change (Acts 11:25' 26). Everyone is called to teach (Matthew 19' 20). Exercising this gift <br />carries with it a greater accountability for the teacher (James 3:1). The goal of this gift is <br />spiritual maturity. (Colossians 1:28-29; 2 Timothy 3:16-17).<br />Some may use this gift in a:</p>

<ul>

<li>Large group - Acts 5:42; 19:11; 20:20</li>

<li>Small group - Acts 2:42; 5:42; 20:20</li>

<li>One-on-one - Acts 18:26; 2 Timothy 2:2</li>

</ul>

<p>Biblical examples:</p>

<ul>

<li>Apollos: Acts 18:24-28</li>

<li>Paul: Acts 18:11; 20:20</li>

<li>Timothy: 2 Timothy 2:2; 4:11</li>

</ul>

<p>Probable characteristics of this gift are:</p>

<ul>

<li>Your prayers are often for understanding with those you are teaching.</li>

<li>You have a great deal of patience for those who are learning from you.</li>

<li>You have the ability to communicate scripture in an understandable way.</li>

<li>You have seen others apply your teachings to their lives and grow as a result.</li>

<li>You are not easily threatened by criticism when teaching.</li>

<li>You enjoy spending time in study for your teaching.</li>

<li>Your study is intended to help you communicate with others.</li>

<li>As a lay person' you find little time for other ministries in addition to teaching.</li>

<li>You may communicate through the use of various media.</li>

<li>You enjoy people.</li>

<li>You have a genuine concern for those you are teaching.</li>

<li>You are concerned that precise words and illustrations you use communicate what you want to say.</li>

<li>You are always learning and then wanting to teach it to others.</li>

<li>You are able to apply truths to the lives of others.</li>

<li>You sometimes feel you could communicate a point better than someone else who is teaching.</li>

<li>You are a disciplined person.</li>

</ul>

<p>The word “pastor” is based on the caring for animals (sheep)' and its function is not well <br />understood today. Jesus is the Good and Ultimate Shepherd of all believers (Psalms 23:1; John <br />10:11' 14; 1 Peter 2:25). Jesus has gifted some as under-shepherds to care for His followers <br />(1 Peter 5:2). This gift is concerned with serving and caring for the needs of a small group of <br />people (1 Peter 5:2-4). This gift is concerned with protecting the believers from attacks' both <br />from within and from the outside (Acts 20:29-31). <br />This is not a passive or docile gift' but must always be alert (Acts 20:29-31). This gift is often <br />combined with other gifts (Ephesians 4:11). This is not the dominant gift of the Senior Pastor for <br />a large growing church. <br />Biblical examples: Acts 20:28-35 -- Ephesians elders <br />Probable characteristics of this gift are:</p>

<ul>

<li>You are a people person and enjoy being around others.</li>

<li>You tend to build deep relationships with others and do not enjoy superficial or casual friendships for very long.</li>

<li>Your prayers are often comprised of requests for the deep hurts and needs of those whom you are shepherding.</li>

<li>Others are attracted to you because they sense that you truly care for them.</li>

<li>People see you as a warm person with a real concern for the welfare of others.</li>

<li>You are frustrated with tasks that take you away from ministering to those around you for very long.</li>

<li>You often see others too involved in their own goals to care for those around themselves.</li>

<li>You do not feel comfortable in a tightly regimented time schedule.</li>

<li>When you share with others' you often focus on the relational aspects of the Christian life.</li>

<li>You feel inadequate to meet all the needs of those to whom you minister.</li>

<li>You have a great burden to protect those around you from non-Biblical influences.</li>

<li>You feel frustrated when relationships with others do not last long-term.</li>

<li>You enjoy being able to focus on a few rather than being “spread too thin.”</li>

</ul>

The length of the statement  "   Most people feel comfortable using a few approaches and these approaches are often what we saw demonstrated in our culture of origin. This may not have been a healthy method of dealing with conflict. " is 199.

The length of the statement  "   Your scores on this report are how YOU see yourself currently dealing with conflict in the environment chosen. This may or may not be accurate depending on how you are aware of yourself in the midst of conflict. It is most helpful to discuss your scores with someone who understands both you and this assessment.  Remember' in the future' the way you approach conflict should be dictated by the situation' not just how you are used to dealing with conflict. In doing so' everyone benefits' including you. " is 504.

The length of the statement " SOLVING describes those who seek to use both RESOLVING and COMPROMISING modes for solving conflict. By combining these two modes' those who seek to solve problems as a team. Their leadership styles are highly cooperative and empowering for the benefit of the entire group.
" is 283.

The length of the statement " ACCOMMODATING combines AVOIDING and YIELDING modes for solving conflict. Those who are ACCOMMODATING are most effective in roles where allowing others to have their way is better for the team. They are often most effective in support roles or roles where an emphasis on the contribution of others is significant.
" is 323.

The length of the statement " A WINNING engagement profile relates to the WINNING mode for solving conflict. Depending on your role' WINNING engagement is important for times when quick decisions need to be made and essential for sole-proprietors. " is 224.

The length of the statement " WINNING is competing and uncooperative. You believe you have the right answer and you must prove you are right whatever it takes. This may be standing up for your own rights' beliefs or position.
" is 206.

The length of the statement " RESOLVING is attempting to work with the other person in depth to find the best solution regardless of where it may lie on the continuum. This involves digging beneath the presenting issue to find a way out that benefits both parties.
" is 245.

The length of the statement " COMPROMISING is finding a middle ground in the conflict. This often involves meeting in the middle or finding some mutually agreeable point between both positions and is useful for quick solutions.
" is 208.

The length of the statement " AVOIDING is not pursuing your own rights or those of the other person. You do not address the conflict. This may be diplomatically sidestepping an issue or avoiding a threatening situation.
" is 200.

The length of the statement " YIELDING is neglecting your own interests and giving in to those of the other person. This is self-sacrifice and may be charity' serving or choosing to obey another when you prefer not to. " is 195.
